However, in real environments, the climate variations and sky types such as overcast, clear and partly cloudy conditions result in ‘nonlinearity’ as well as ‘uncertainty’ in the amount of exterior daylight penetration into interiors. Accordingly, establishing an integrated and intelligent lighting concept is very important part of the lighting design process. The major integration issues involved are: (a) forming an online self-adaptive control algorithm capable of real-time prediction of daylight illuminance in the interior, (b) developing a real-time control strategy for intelligent automated control of electric lights and window blinds, (c) maximising utilisation of daylight and minimising consumption of electrical energy and (d) providing better visual comfort. This study was initiated after encouraging editorial comments and recommendations to previous published work.9 For real-time measurement, prediction and control, the application of data driven techniques for modelling could be utilised to quickly identify and predict the behaviour of the underlying dynamic illuminance process. In adaptive schemes the performance feedback is utilised directly to change the model parameters through systematic procedures called ‘learning’ or ‘training’ rules, so that the output changes with respect to the desired goal. More specifically, the objectives of this paper are:


to form a five step ahead online time series predictor of daylight illuminance that would facilitate advance decisions on control signal generation;

to develop an online self-tuning algorithm for updating the model online to account for the prediction and control error due to environmental variations;

to devise a prototype system based on an online self-adaptive, predictive model for electric light and window blind control for maximising utilisation of quality daylight and minimising lighting energy consumption without impairing visual comfort; and

to carry out real-time integration and validation of controller routines to create a multifunctional personal computer (PC) based electric light and window blind control system.
